/*

    Click and drag the mouse to change the slope.

    The pattern in the voxels must obey a recursively applied rule to form a linear pattern:

    - The step sizes come in two quantities which have a difference of 1.
    - One step size is the common while the other is the rare. The common step size may occur several times consecutively but the rare type
      may not repeat.
    - The number of consecutive repetitions of the common step size may only come in two quantities which have a difference of 1.
    - One number of consecutive repititions is the common type and the other is the rare type. Like the step sizes, the common may repeat but
      the rare may not repeat.
    etc.

    The more complex the ratio of the slope, the larger the cycle, the more chaotic it appears when the volume expands or retracts. The rules
    also become more abstract the further removed it becomes from the original step size.

*/



void mainImage( out vec4 fragColor, in vec2 fragCoord )
{
    float grid_size = 20.0;

    vec2 grid_square = vec2(
        floor((fragCoord.x - 0.5*iResolution.x + 0.5*grid_size)/grid_size),
        floor((fragCoord.y - 0.5*iResolution.y + 0.5*grid_size)/grid_size)
    );

    if(dot(normalize(iMouse.xy - 0.5*iResolution.xy), grid_square) + 5.0*sin(iTime*0.5) < 0.0) {
        fragColor = vec4(0.0, 0.0, 0.0, 1.0);
    } else fragColor = vec4(1.0, 1.0, 1.0, 1.0);

    if(dot(normalize(iMouse.xy - 0.5*iResolution.xy), fragCoord.xy - 0.5*iResolution.xy) + grid_size*5.0*sin(iTime*0.5) < 0.5) {
        fragColor = 0.5*(fragColor + vec4(0.5, 0.0, 0.0, 1.0));
    }
}
